{{Infobox person | name = Mohamad Fakih | image = |birth_name = Mohamad Abdallah Fakih |birth_date = May, 1971<ref>{{cite web|title=Mohamad Abdallah FAKIH - Personal Appointments|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/officers/KgdDt44F7eSFYAmsDTZmsGEFYjM/appointments|publisher=[[Companies House]]|accessdate=6 April 2017|language=en}}</ref> |birth_place = [[Lebanon|Beirut, Lebanon]] |nationality = Canadian | occupation = Entrepreneur, CEO, Philanthropist | yearsactive = 1997–present | known_for = Paramount Fine Foods<ref>{{cite news|title=Q&A: Mohamad Fakih, the restaurant CEO who paid for funerals for the Quebec mosque shooting victims|url=http://torontolife.com/city/life/qa-mohmad-fakih/|accessdate=2 April 2017|work=[[Toronto Life]]|date=15 February 2017}}</ref> | website = }}
'''Mohamad Abdallah Fakih''' is a Lebanese-Canadian businessman and philanthropist. He started Paramount Fine Foods after arriving in Canada as an immigrant. In May 2018, Fakih was awarded an honourary doctorate from Ryerson University <ref>{{cite news|title=Canadian CEO Steps Up To Pay Funeral Costs For Quebec Victims|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2017/02/01/mohamad-fakih-quebec-mosque-attack-funerals_n_14529496.html|accessdate=2 April 2017|work=[[The Huffington Post]] Canada}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Mohamad Fakih is building a Middle Eastern restaurant empire in Canada- Canadian Immigrant|url=http://canadianimmigrant.ca/immigrant-stories/entrepreneur-immigrants/mohamad-fakih-is-building-a-middle-eastern-restaurant-empire-in-canada|accessdate=2 April 2017|work=[[Canadian Immigrant]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=How I turned a struggling Lebanese restaurant into a successful 20-outlet chain|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/small-business/startups/how-i-turned-a-struggling-ethnic-restaurant-into-a-successful-20-outlet-chain/article26357914/|publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]]|accessdate=2 April 2017|language=en-ca}}</ref> Fakih is also known for partnering with Ryerson University to connect employers looking to hire to newly arrived Syrians.<ref>{{cite news|title=Syrian newcomers are 'assets,' says Toronto restaurateur who is hiring them|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/programs/metromorning/paramount-syrian-refugee-hiring-1.3500761|accessdate=2 April 2017|work=[[CBC.ca]]|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=In the time of Trump, founder of Paramount restaurants is thinking way beyond shawarma - Toronto Star|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/insight/2017/03/25/paramount-restaurants-founders-vision-goes-beyond-food.html|accessdate=2 April 2017|work=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref> In 2014, Fakih protested against Toronto graffiti stating "Arab go home" referencing the [[Gaza–Israel conflict|Gaza conflict]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Mohamad Fakih: In wake of heinous Toronto graffiti, everybody should be advocating for peace|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/toronto/mohamad-fakih-in-wake-of-heinous-toronto-graffiti-everybody-should-be-advocating-for-peace|accessdate=2 April 2017|work=[[National Post]]|language=en}}</ref>
== Career== '''Paramount Fine Foods'''
Mohamad Fakih was born to Abdallah and Nabiha in Beirut, Lebanon.<ref>{{cite news|title=In the time of Trump, founder of Paramount restaurants is thinking way beyond shawarma - Toronto Star|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/insight/2017/03/25/paramount-restaurants-founders-vision-goes-beyond-food.html|accessdate=2 April 2017|work=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref> In 1997, Fakih opened a jewelry store in Lebanon.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Guardian|first1=Brampton|title=Success tips from Paramount’s CEO include taking great leaps of faith|url=http://www.bramptonguardian.com/opinion-story/6871152-success-tips-from-paramount-s-ceo-include-taking-great-leaps-of-faith/|accessdate=2 April 2017|work=www.bramptonguardian.com}}</ref> He moved to Canada in 1999.<ref>{{cite news|title=How one businessman shows off what’s possible in Canada to his new refugee recruits from Syria|url=http://business.financialpost.com/executive/leadership/how-one-businessman-shows-off-whats-possible-in-canada-to-his-new-refugee-recruits-from-syria|accessdate=2 April 2017|work=[[Financial Post]]|language=en}}</ref> In 2006, Fakih founded Paramount Fine Foods. Paramount Fine Foods now has over 80 restaurants across North America. In April 2018, the City of Mississauga announced that the city's sports arena, the Hershey Centre, would be renamed the Paramount Centre. In May 2018, Fakih was awarded an honourary doctorate from Ryerson University.<ref>{{cite news|title=Voices of Our Toronto: Mohamad Fakih|url=http://www.cbc.ca/player/play/2677951894|accessdate=2 April 2017|work=[[CBC.ca]]|date=28 October 2015|language=en-CA}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Paramount Fine Foods|url=http://www.cbj.ca/paramount-fine-foods/|accessdate=2 April 2017|work=The Canadian Business Journal|date=29 January 2015|language=en-CA}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Meet The Immigrant CEO Welcoming Syrian Refugees To Canada With Jobs|url=http://www.newsy.com/stories/meet-the-immigrant-ceo-welcoming-syrian-refugees-to-canada-with-jobs/|publisher=[[Newsy]]|accessdate=2 April 2017|language=en}}</ref>
'''Philanthropy''' In 2015, Fakih partnered with [[Ryerson University]] for the lifeline Syrian challenge to settle Syrian refugees.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mohamad Fakih and Paramount Fine Foods Take Action to Help Settle Syrian Refugees - Lifeline Syria - Ryerson University|url=http://www.ryerson.ca/lifelinesyria/media/20160315/|publisher=[[Ryerson University]]|accessdate=2 April 2017|language=en}}</ref> Since the partnership began, Fakih has hired over 150 Syrian refugees across Paramount Fine Foods locations. Fakih has also been involved in a number of other philanthropic initiatives, including a partnership with the UNHCR, announced in May 2018. He paid for funeral costs for the victims of the 2016 Quebec mosque shooting, and for the mosque repairs. He also paid for dozens of hotel rooms for homeless people during a 2017-2018 cold weather crisis in Toronto.<ref>{{cite web|title=Paramount Fine Foods CEO urges Ontario business community to hire Syrian refugees|url=http://www.mississauga.com/news-story/6889367-paramount-fine-foods-ceo-urges-ontario-business-community-to-hire-syrian-refugees/|publisher=[[The Mississauga News]]|accessdate=2 April 2017}}</ref>
'''Lawsuit'''
In 2017, Fakih sued Mississauga journalist Kevin J. Johnston of FreedomReport.ca for defamation after videos released asking questions about his ties to the Pakistan Spy Agency ISI, and links to extremism.<ref>https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/restaurateur-sues-two-for-defamation-after-being-accused-of-links-to-extremism/article35980400/</ref>
